(44, 14, 1, 44, 18, 4, 4, 'both of the Jews and also of the Greeks believed', 'Jewish and Greek Believers', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of Jews and Greeks in the audience. They highlight the success of the apostles in persuading both groups to believe.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 1, 44, 13, 46, 46, 'both of the Jews and also of the Greeks believed', 'Connection of Belief in Gentiles', 'Both passages emphasize the belief of Gentiles in the message of God. Acts 14:1 shows a great multitude of Greeks believing, while Acts 13:46 indicates a shift to the Gentiles after the Jews rejected the message.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 1, 45, 1, 16, 16, 'both of the Jews and also of the Greeks believed', 'Connection of Belief in Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize belief among Jews and Greeks. Acts 14:1 mentions a multitude of believers, while Romans 1:16 states the gospel is for ''the Jew first, and also to the Greek.'' This connection highlights the inclusivity of the gospel message.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 1, 45, 10, 12, 12, 'both of the Jews and also of the Greeks believed', 'Unity of Believers in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the inclusion of both Jews and Greeks in the faith. Acts 14:1 mentions a great multitude of Jews and Greeks believing, while Romans 10:12 states there is no difference between them in calling upon the Lord.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 1, 46, 1, 22, 24, 'both of the Jews and also of the Greeks believed', 'Jews and Greeks Believing', 'Both passages emphasize the belief of Jews and Greeks in Christ. Acts 14:1 mentions a great multitude of both groups believing, while 1 Corinthians 1:22-24 discusses their differing responses to the message of Christ. This connection highlights the universal call to faith among diverse audiences.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 1, 48, 3, 28, 28, 'both of the Jews and also of the Greeks', 'Unity in Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the inclusion of Jews and Greeks in the faith. This connection highlights the idea of unity among believers, regardless of their ethnic backgrounds.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 1, 43, 7, 35, 35, 'both of the Jews and also of the Greeks believed', 'Connection of Belief and Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize the spread of belief among Jews and Gentiles. Acts 14:1 shows the success of teaching in Iconium, while John 7:35 raises the question of teaching the dispersed among Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 2, 44, 13, 50, 50, 'stirred up the Gentiles', 'Persecution by Unbelieving Jews', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Jews in stirring up opposition against Paul and Barnabas. In Acts 13:50, the Jews incite persecution, while in Acts 14:2, they influence the Gentiles against the brethren.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 2, 44, 14, 19, 19, 'unbelieving Jews stirred up the Gentiles', 'Opposition to Paul and Believers', 'Both passages emphasize the role of unbelieving Jews in inciting hostility against Paul and the brethren. In Acts 14:2, the Jews stir up the Gentiles, while in Acts 14:19, Jews persuade the people to stone Paul, demonstrating a continued pattern of opposition.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 2, 52, 2, 15, 16, 'made their minds evil affected against the brethren', 'Persecution of Believers', 'Both passages emphasize the hostility faced by believers from the Jews. Acts 14:2 describes the Jews stirring up opposition against the brethren, while 1 Thessalonians 2:15-16 details their persecution of the apostles and their efforts to prevent Gentile salvation.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 2, 41, 15, 10, 11, 'made their minds evil affected', 'Influence of Unbelief and Envy', 'This connection highlights how both passages depict the influence of negative sentiments—unbelief in Acts and envy in Mark—leading to opposition against the faithful. In both cases, these emotions stir up the people against the brethren or Jesus.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 2, 43, 3, 36, 36, NULL, 'Belief and Unbelief Consequences', 'This connection highlights the consequences of belief and unbelief. Acts 14:2 discusses how unbelieving Jews influenced others negatively, while John 3:36 emphasizes the eternal consequences for those who do not believe in the Son.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 3, 58, 2, 4, 4, 'signs and wonders', 'Connection of Signs and Wonders', 'Both passages emphasize God''s testimony through signs and wonders. This connection highlights the divine validation of the message through miraculous acts.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 3, 44, 20, 32, 32, 'the word of his grace', 'Connection of Grace in Acts', 'Both passages emphasize ''the word of his grace,'' highlighting its significance in the ministry and the believers'' growth. This connection illustrates the continuity of grace as a central theme in the early church.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 3, 49, 6, 18, 20, 'speaking boldly', 'Boldness in Proclamation', 'This connection highlights the theme of boldness in speaking about the gospel. Both passages emphasize the importance of proclaiming the message with confidence, as seen in the phrases about speaking boldly.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 3, 44, 20, 24, 24, 'the word of his grace', 'Connection of Grace and Testimony', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of testifying to the grace of God. Acts 14:3 mentions ''the word of his grace,'' while Acts 20:24 refers to ''the gospel of the grace of God.''', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 3, 41, 16, 20, 20, 'signs and wonders', 'Signs and Wonders Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Lord in confirming the message through signs and wonders. Acts 14:3 mentions ''signs and wonders'' being done by the apostles, while Mark 16:20 states that the Lord confirmed the word with ''signs following.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 3, 45, 1, 16, 16, NULL, 'Power of God and Gospel', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine power in both passages. Acts 14:3 mentions ''signs and wonders'' as evidence of God''s grace, while Romans 1:16 emphasizes the gospel as ''the power of God unto salvation.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 3, 52, 2, 2, 2, 'speaking boldly in the Lord', 'Boldness in Speaking the Gospel', 'This connection highlights the theme of boldness in proclaiming the gospel despite challenges. Both passages emphasize speaking boldly in the Lord and in God, showcasing the perseverance of the apostles in their ministry.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 4, 44, 28, 24, 24, 'part held with the Jews', 'Division of Belief', 'Both passages emphasize a division among people regarding belief. In Acts 14:4, part of the multitude sided with the Jews, while in Acts 28:24, some believed and some did not.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 4, 42, 11, 21, 23, 'divided', 'Division and Allegiance', 'This connection highlights the theme of division among people regarding allegiance. Both passages emphasize the necessity of choosing sides, as seen in the division in Acts and the call to be with or against in Luke.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 4, 44, 14, 14, 14, 'the multitude of the city was divided', 'Response to Division Among People', 'This connection highlights the reaction of the apostles to the division in the city. Both passages emphasize the apostles'' urgency in addressing the people''s divided opinions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 4, 33, 7, 6, 6, 'the multitude of the city was divided', 'Division and Familial Conflict', 'This connection highlights the theme of division among people, as seen in Acts where the multitude is divided. Similarly, Micah describes familial conflict, indicating that divisions can occur even among close relationships.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 4, 40, 10, 34, 36, 'the multitude of the city was divided', 'Division and Conflict in Relationships', 'Both passages emphasize division among people, with Acts 14:4 highlighting a city divided and Matthew 10:34-36 discussing familial conflict. This connection highlights the theme of discord arising from differing beliefs.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 4, 42, 2, 34, 34, NULL, 'Division and Opposition in Israel', 'This connection highlights the theme of division and opposition within Israel. In Acts 14:4, the multitude is divided, while in Luke 2:34, Simeon speaks of a child who will be a sign spoken against, indicating conflict and differing responses among the people.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 4, 43, 7, 43, 43, NULL, 'Division Among the People', 'Both passages emphasize the division among the people, highlighting differing opinions and allegiances. In Acts, the division is between Jews and apostles, while in John, it is among the people regarding Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 5, 44, 14, 19, 19, 'assault made both of the Gentiles, and also of the Jews', 'Assault and Stoning of Paul', 'Both passages emphasize the violent opposition faced by Paul and his companions. The assault mentioned in Acts 14:5 foreshadows the stoning of Paul in Acts 14:19, illustrating the escalating hostility from both Jews and Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 5, 55, 3, 11, 11, NULL, 'Persecution and Deliverance Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of persecution faced by Paul and others. Acts 14:5 describes an assault against them, while 2 Timothy 3:11 recounts the specific persecutions Paul endured and God''s deliverance.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 5, 44, 4, 25, 29, NULL, 'Opposition to God''s Messengers', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of rulers against God''s chosen, highlighting the theme of opposition faced by His servants. The assault in Acts 14:5 parallels the threats described in Acts 4:25-29, illustrating a consistent pattern of resistance from both Gentiles and Jews.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 5, 19, 2, 1, 3, NULL, 'Rulers Against the Anointed', 'Both passages emphasize the opposition of rulers against God''s messengers. In Acts, the rulers conspire to harm Paul and Barnabas, paralleling the rebellion of rulers against the Lord in Psalms.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 5, 19, 83, 5, 5, 'assault made both of the Gentiles', 'Assault and Confederacy Against Believers', 'This connection highlights the theme of opposition faced by believers. Both passages emphasize a united front against God''s messengers, with Acts describing an assault and Psalms noting a confederacy.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 5, 40, 5, 44, 44, NULL, 'Connection of Love and Persecution', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of responding to persecution with love and kindness. Acts 14:5 describes being despitefully used, while Matthew 5:44 instructs to pray for those who despitefully use you.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 5, 42, 6, 28, 28, NULL, 'Response to Persecution', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of responding to mistreatment. Acts 14:5 describes being treated ''despitefully,'' while Luke 6:28 instructs to ''bless them that curse you'' and pray for those who use you despitefully.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 6, 40, 10, 23, 23, 'fled unto Lystra and Derbe', 'Fleeing from Persecution', 'Both passages emphasize the act of fleeing to another city in response to persecution. Acts 14:6 describes fleeing to Lystra and Derbe, while Matthew 10:23 instructs to flee into another city when persecuted.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 6, 44, 14, 20, 21, 'fled unto Lystra and Derbe', 'Journey to Lystra and Derbe', 'This connection highlights the movement of Paul and Barnabas as they travel to Lystra and Derbe. Both passages emphasize their missionary efforts in these cities, illustrating the continuity of their journey.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 6, 55, 3, 11, 11, 'Lystra', 'Connection of Persecution and Location', 'This connection highlights the shared mention of Lystra in both passages, emphasizing the significance of this city in the context of persecution faced by Paul. Both passages emphasize the challenges endured by Paul in Lystra and the surrounding regions.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 6, 44, 16, 1, 2, 'Lystra and Derbe', 'Connection between Lystra and Derbe', 'Both passages emphasize the cities of Lystra and Derbe, indicating their significance in Paul''s missionary journey. The mention of these locations in both verses highlights their role in the spread of early Christianity.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 6, 12, 6, 8, 12, 'fled unto Lystra and Derbe', 'Divine Warning and Escape', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine warning leading to escape. In both passages, individuals receive guidance from a prophet that enables them to avoid danger and flee to safety.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 7, 44, 14, 21, 21, 'preached the gospel', 'Preaching the Gospel Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of preaching the gospel in different locations. The continuity of preaching is evident as the apostles move from one city to another, reinforcing their mission.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 7, 44, 16, 10, 10, 'preached the gospel', 'Preaching the Gospel Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the act of preaching the gospel. In Acts 14:7, the focus is on the initial preaching, while Acts 16:10 highlights a specific calling to preach in Macedonia.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 7, 52, 2, 2, 2, 'preached the gospel', 'Preaching the Gospel Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of preaching the gospel despite challenges. Acts 14:7 mentions the preaching of the gospel, while 1 Thessalonians 2:2 highlights boldness in speaking the gospel amid contention.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 7, 55, 4, 2, 2, 'preached the gospel', 'Connection of Preaching the Gospel', 'This connection highlights the act of preaching in both passages. Acts 14:7 emphasizes the preaching of the gospel, while 2 Timothy 4:2 instructs to ''preach the word,'' underscoring the importance of sharing the message consistently.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 7, 44, 8, 4, 4, 'preached the gospel', 'Preaching the Gospel Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the act of preaching the gospel. Acts 14:7 states that they preached the gospel, while Acts 8:4 describes those scattered preaching the word everywhere.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 7, 44, 11, 19, 19, 'preached the gospel', 'Preaching the Gospel Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the act of preaching the gospel. Acts 11:19 describes the initial spread of the message, while Acts 14:7 highlights its continued proclamation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 8, 44, 3, 2, 2, NULL, 'Lameness from Birth', 'Both passages emphasize a man lame from his mother’s womb, highlighting the miraculous healing of individuals who had never walked. This connection illustrates the theme of divine intervention in the lives of those with physical disabilities.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 8, 43, 5, 3, 5, 'impotent in his feet', 'Healing of the Crippled', 'Both passages emphasize individuals who are described as ''impotent'' and suffering from physical disabilities. The healing of the crippled man in Acts parallels the account of the man with an infirmity in John, highlighting themes of miraculous restoration.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 8, 43, 5, 7, 7, 'impotent in his feet', 'Connection of Impotence and Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the condition of being ''impotent'' and the struggle for healing. The man in Lystra and the man by the pool both represent individuals unable to walk, highlighting themes of physical disability and the need for divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 8, 43, 9, 1, 2, 'from his mother’s womb', 'Connection of Physical Impairment', 'This connection highlights the theme of individuals suffering from physical disabilities from birth. Both passages emphasize the condition of being ''blind from his birth'' and ''cripple from his mother’s womb,'' illustrating the plight of those with congenital ailments.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 8, 44, 4, 9, 9, NULL, 'Connection of Impotent Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of an impotent man. Acts 14:8 describes the man''s condition, while Acts 4:9 refers to the good deed done to him, linking their narratives of miraculous healing.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 9, 40, 15, 28, 28, 'faith to be healed', 'Faith and Healing Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of faith leading to healing in both passages. In Acts, Paul perceives faith in the man, while in Matthew, Jesus acknowledges the woman''s great faith, resulting in healing.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 9, 44, 3, 4, 4, 'stedfastly beholding him', 'Connection of Healing Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the act of looking intently at someone in need of healing. In Acts 14:9, Paul perceives the man''s faith to be healed, while in Acts 3:4, Peter commands the man to look at them, indicating a focus on faith and healing.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 9, 40, 9, 28, 29, 'faith to be healed', 'Faith and Healing Connection', 'This connection highlights the role of faith in healing. Both passages emphasize that healing is linked to the individual''s faith, as seen in Paul''s perception of the man''s faith and Jesus'' response to the blind men''s belief.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 9, 41, 1, 40, 41, 'faith to be healed', 'Connection of Healing Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of faith in healing. In Acts, Paul perceives the man''s faith to be healed, while in Mark, the leper expresses faith in Jesus'' ability to cleanse him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 9, 41, 2, 5, 5, 'faith to be healed', 'Connection of Faith in Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the role of faith in healing. In Acts, Paul perceives the man''s faith to be healed, while in Mark, Jesus acknowledges the faith of those bringing the sick man. This connection highlights the importance of faith in the context of miraculous healing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 10, 23, 35, 6, 6, 'leaped and walked', 'Healing and Restoration Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the miraculous healing of the lame. In Acts, the man stands and walks, while Isaiah foretells the lame leaping, highlighting a theme of restoration and divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 10, 43, 5, 8, 9, 'walk', 'Healing and Restoration', 'Both passages emphasize the command to ''walk'' as a sign of healing. The miraculous acts in each instance demonstrate the power of faith and the restoration of physical ability.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 10, 43, 14, 12, 12, 'Stand upright on thy feet', 'Connection of Healing and Belief', 'This connection highlights the theme of miraculous works through faith. In Acts, the healing of the man emphasizes the power of belief, while John speaks of believers doing greater works, suggesting a continuation of miraculous acts through faith in Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 10, 42, 7, 14, 14, 'Stand upright on thy feet', 'Healing and Resurrection Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of restoration to life. Both passages emphasize the command to arise, leading to miraculous healing and revival.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 10, 42, 13, 11, 13, 'Stand upright on thy feet', 'Healing and Restoration', 'Both passages emphasize miraculous healing, with individuals being restored to health. The command to ''stand upright'' in Acts parallels the woman''s restoration to being ''made straight'' in Luke.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 10, 44, 3, 6, 8, 'Stand upright on thy feet', 'Healing and Restoration', 'Both passages emphasize miraculous healing, where individuals are commanded to ''rise up and walk.'' This connection highlights the power of faith and the authority of the apostles in performing miracles in the name of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 10, 44, 9, 33, 34, 'Stand upright on thy feet', 'Healing Miracles by Apostles', 'Both passages emphasize miraculous healings performed by apostles, showcasing their authority to restore health. The command to ''arise'' in both instances signifies a transformative act of healing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 11, 44, 28, 6, 6, 'The gods are come down to us', 'Divine Recognition of Paul', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s reaction to Paul, who is perceived as a divine figure. In Acts 14:11, the crowd declares him a god, while in Acts 28:6, they change their minds and also call him a god after witnessing his survival.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 11, 44, 8, 10, 10, 'the gods are come down to us', 'Recognition of Divine Power', 'This connection highlights how both passages emphasize the people''s recognition of extraordinary power in human form. In Acts 14:11, the people mistake Paul for a god, while in Acts 8:10, they attribute divine power to another figure. Both instances reflect a response to miraculous acts.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 11, 44, 12, 22, 22, 'the gods are come down to us', 'Divine Recognition by People', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s recognition of Paul and Herod as divine figures. In Acts 14:11, the crowd declares Paul a god, while in Acts 12:22, they proclaim Herod''s voice as that of a god.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 12, 44, 19, 35, 35, 'Jupiter', 'Connection through Jupiter reference', 'Both passages emphasize the figure of Jupiter, linking the cultural context of worship in Lystra and Ephesus. This connection highlights the significance of Roman deities in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 13, 27, 2, 46, 46, NULL, 'Worship and Sacrifice Themes', 'Both passages emphasize acts of worship and sacrifice. In Acts, the priest of Jupiter seeks to offer sacrifices, while in Daniel, Nebuchadnezzar commands offerings to Daniel. This connection highlights the theme of reverence shown to individuals in positions of perceived power.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 13, 44, 10, 25, 25, NULL, 'Worship and Sacrifice', 'This connection highlights the theme of worship, as both passages depict individuals offering reverence. In Acts 14:13, the priest of Jupiter seeks to sacrifice, while in Acts 10:25, Cornelius worships Peter, indicating a similar act of devotion.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 14, 40, 26, 65, 65, 'rent their clothes', 'Rending of Clothes', 'This connection highlights the act of rending clothes as a response to perceived blasphemy. Both passages emphasize a strong emotional reaction to statements considered offensive or sacrilegious.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 14, 12, 5, 7, 7, 'rent their clothes', 'Clothing as a Sign of Distress', 'Both passages emphasize the act of rending clothes as a response to distress. In Acts, Paul and Barnabas tear their garments in reaction to the people''s misguided worship, while in 2 Kings, the king of Israel tears his clothes in despair over a perceived threat.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 14, 15, 9, 3, 5, 'rent their clothes', 'Expressions of Grief and Distress', 'Both passages emphasize the act of rending garments as a sign of deep emotional distress. This connection highlights a shared cultural expression of mourning and astonishment in response to troubling events.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 14, 24, 36, 24, 24, 'rent their clothes', 'Response to Rejection', 'This connection highlights the contrasting reactions to divine messages. In Acts 14:14, the apostles express deep distress by rending their clothes, while in Jeremiah 36:24, the king and his servants show no fear or similar response. Both passages emphasize the significance of emotional responses to God''s word.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 14, 46, 9, 5, 6, 'Barnabas and Paul', 'Connection Between Apostolic Authority', 'This connection highlights the authority of Barnabas and Paul as apostles. Both passages emphasize their roles and rights within the early church, particularly regarding their ability to lead and work.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 14, 41, 14, 63, 63, 'rent their clothes', 'Rending of Clothes', 'This connection highlights the act of rending clothes as a response to profound distress or outrage. Both passages emphasize this physical expression of emotion in critical moments.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 15, 44, 10, 26, 26, NULL, 'Humanity of Apostles', 'Both passages emphasize the humanity of the apostles, as they identify themselves as ''men'' and share a common experience with the people. This connection highlights their role as mediators between God and humanity.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 15, 46, 8, 4, 4, 'the living God', 'Connection Between Idols and God', 'Both passages emphasize the distinction between the living God and idols. Acts 14:15 speaks of turning to the living God, while 1 Corinthians 8:4 asserts that an idol is nothing, reinforcing the idea of God''s uniqueness.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 15, 59, 5, 17, 17, 'men of like passions', 'Connection of Human Experience', 'This connection highlights the shared human experience of the speakers in both passages. Both emphasize that they are ''men of like passions'' and demonstrate how ordinary individuals can engage with the divine.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 15, 9, 12, 21, 21, NULL, 'Vain Things and Living God', 'Both passages emphasize the futility of pursuing vain things. Acts 14:15 encourages turning to the living God, while 1 Samuel 12:21 warns against following vain things that cannot profit.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 15, 19, 146, 5, 6, 'which made heaven, and earth, and the sea, and all things that are therein', 'Creation and Divine Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the God who ''made heaven, and earth, and the sea, and all things that are therein.'' This connection highlights the recognition of God''s sovereignty and creative power in both texts.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 15, 1, 1, 1, 1, 'which made heaven, and earth', 'Creation and the Living God', 'Both passages emphasize the act of creation, with Acts 14:15 referencing the ''living God'' who made ''heaven, and earth,'' paralleling Genesis 1:1''s declaration of God''s creation of ''the heaven and the earth.'' This connection highlights the foundational belief in God as the creator in both texts.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 15, 24, 14, 22, 22, 'vanities', 'Connection of Vanities and Creation', 'Both passages emphasize the futility of vanities and affirm the sovereignty of God as the creator of all things. Acts 14:15 calls for a turn from vanities to the living God, while Jeremiah 14:22 questions the ability of Gentile vanities to provide rain, acknowledging God as the true creator.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 16, 44, 17, 30, 30, 'suffered all nations to walk in their own ways', 'God''s Response to Ignorance', 'Both passages emphasize God''s previous tolerance of human ignorance. Acts 14:16 notes that God allowed nations to walk in their own ways, while Acts 17:30 indicates a shift where God now commands repentance from this ignorance.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 16, 19, 81, 12, 12, 'walk in their own ways', 'Connection of Human Autonomy', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of allowing nations or people to follow their own ways or desires. Acts 14:16 notes that God permitted nations to walk in their own ways, while Psalms 81:12 reflects God giving people up to their own hearts'' lusts.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 16, 19, 147, 20, 20, 'all nations to walk in their own ways', 'Divine Sovereignty Over Nations', 'This connection highlights God''s unique relationship with nations. Acts 14:16 mentions God''s allowance for nations to walk in their own ways, while Psalms 147:20 emphasizes that He has not dealt so with any nation, indicating a distinction in His judgments.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 16, 45, 1, 28, 28, 'walk in their own ways', 'Divine Allowance and Human Rejection', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s allowance for nations to follow their own ways, which leads to a rejection of divine knowledge. Both passages emphasize the consequences of turning away from God, resulting in a reprobate mind.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 16, 33, 4, 5, 5, 'walk in their own ways', 'Walking in God''s Ways', 'This connection highlights the theme of walking in the ways of one''s chosen deity. Acts 14:16 notes that nations walked in their own ways, while Micah 4:5 contrasts this by emphasizing walking in the name of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 16, 45, 1, 21, 25, 'walk in their own ways', 'Divine Allowance and Human Rebellion', 'Both passages emphasize God''s allowance for nations to follow their own ways, leading to a rejection of His glory. This connection highlights the consequences of turning away from God and the resulting moral decline.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 16, 49, 2, 12, 12, 'walk in their own ways', 'God''s Allowance of Alienation', 'This connection highlights the theme of alienation from God. Acts 14:16 speaks of God''s past allowance for nations to walk in their own ways, while Ephesians 2:12 describes being without God and alienated from His promises.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 17, 45, 1, 19, 20, 'he left not himself without witness', 'Divine Witness and Creation', 'Both passages emphasize God''s revelation through creation. Acts 14:17 speaks of God''s goodness and provision, while Romans 1:19-20 highlights how God''s attributes are evident in creation, leaving humanity without excuse.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 17, 29, 2, 23, 23, 'rain from heaven, and fruitful seasons', 'Connection of Rain and Gladness', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of rain as a blessing from God that brings joy and sustenance. Acts 14:17 mentions rain and gladness, while Joel 2:23 speaks of rain and rejoicing in the Lord.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
